## 🐛 Bug Report

- When trying to read an excel file, the array containing each row columns values doesn't return the last cell if it's empty (the same problem if we have more consecutive empty cells at the end of the row, they don't get returned)
I tried this option: { includeEmpty: true } but it works just if the cells are in the middle of the row not at the end.

- the arrays returned also contain always an empty field (null), in the beginning, even though there is not an empty cell at the beginning of each row in the excel file 

Lib version: 4.1.1

## Steps To Reproduce

```javascript
                        const wb = new ExcelJS.Workbook();
			const reader = new FileReader()
			reader.readAsArrayBuffer(this.file)
			reader.onload = () => {
				const buffer = reader.result;
				wb.xlsx.load(buffer).then(workbook => {
					workbook.eachSheet((sheet, id) => {
						sheet.eachRow({ includeEmpty: true }, (row, rowIndex) => {
							console.log(row.values, row.values.length, rowIndex)
							if(rowIndex !== 1) this.fileArrayData.push(row.values.splice(1))
						})
					})
				}).catch(error => {
				})
			}
```

## The expected behaviour:

Get an array of each row without the empty field (null) at the beginning of each one of them
Get the last consecutive cells even if they are empty.

